<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-01-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-01-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="493" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d493">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">611.00/1–454</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of
                            State</hi><note n="1" xml:id="d493fn1">Drafted by Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>.</note></head>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi></seg>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-01-04">January 4,
                                1954</date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">[Extract]</note>
                    <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                    <p>Senator <persName>George</persName> brought up Indochina. He was greatly
                        worried about that situation. He hopes that no effort will be made to get
                        Congress’ <pb facs="0972" n="940" xml:id="pg_940"/> consent to sending in
                        U.S. troops. We talked about possible sea and air activity, to which he did
                        not seem seriously to object.</p>
                    <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>